'''Lee Remmel''' is a retired public relations/historian/spokesman and sportswriter. He is known for working 62 years with the [[Green Bay Packers]] as a sportswriter and later a team employee.<ref>{{cite web | title=Packers.com - History - Ask Lee Remmel | work=Packers.com | url = http://www.packers.com/history/ask_lee_remmel/ | accessdate=May 6 | accessyear=2008}}</ref>  

Remmel was born in [[Shawano, Wisconsin]], a small town about 30 miles outside of [[Green Bay, Wisconsin]]. He began writing as a [[freshman]] at Shawano high school<ref name=WGBA /> and went to his first Packers game on [[September 24]] [[1944]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Remmel's run with Packers draws to a close; with photo gallery | work=[[Green Bay Press-Gazette]] | url = http://www.greenbaypressgazette.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20071212/GPG0101/712120716/1989 | accessdate=May 7 | accessyear=2008}}</ref> On [[October 7]] [[1945]], Remmel started covering the Green Bay Packers as a sportswriter for the ''Green Bay Press Gazette''.<ref name=GBHOF /> He was the only sportswriter who had covered all of the Packers coaches from the team's first coach [[Curly Lambeau]] to [[Bart Starr]].<ref name=WGBA /> He was hired to work in the Packers front office in 1974<ref name=GBHOF>{{cite web | title=Green Bay Packers Hall of Fame - Lee Remmel | work=PackersHallofFame.org | url = http://www.packershalloffame.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=150&Itemid=58 | accessdate=May 4 | accessyear=2008}}</ref> as the teams public relations director and spokesman.<ref name=WGBA>{{cite web | title=Lee Remmel to Retire from Packers | work=[[WGBA]] | url = http://www.nbc26.com/sports/local/12437051.html | accessdate=May 6 | accessyear=2008}}</ref> In February 2004, Remmel was named the historian for the Green Bay Packers,<ref>{{cite web | title=Lee Remmel, Green Bay Packers Team Historian, To Retire After 62-Year Association With Franchise | work=Packers.com | url = http://www.packers.com/news/releases/2007/12/12/1/ | accessdate=May 6 | accessyear=2008}}</ref> a role he served until his retirement in December of 2007 at age 83.<ref>{{cite web | title=Remmel's career one for the ages | work=[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]] | url = http://www.jsonline.com/story/index.aspx?id=696261 | accessdate=May 6 | accessyear=2008}}</ref> He remained on the board of directors for the [[Green Bay Packers Hall of Fame]].

Remmel was involved with staffing the first forty [[Superbowl]]s. He represented the Press Gazette at the first eight, 22 as NFL auxiliary media relations staff, two years for the Green Bay Packers, and another eight with the NFL.<ref name=WGBA /> He was one of twelve people honored by the NFL for their association with the first forty Superbowls.<ref name=WGBA /> Remmel has served on NFL committees on  statistics and [[NFL Films]], and participated in the NFL public relations directors' Professional Football Writers of America liaison.<ref name=WGBA />

Remmel is known for his in-depth knowledge of Packer's history, especially about the team's rivalry with the [[Chicago Bears]]. Former Packers [[quarterback]] [[Brett Favre]] described Remmel, "He<U+2019>s a Packers icon. There will never be another like him. His knowledge of the team and its history has always been impressive. He is sharp as a tack when it came to those things <U+2013> truly impressive."<ref name=WGBA />

==Awards==
Remmel was named Wisconsin's Sports Writer of the year in 1967.<ref name=WGBA /> Remmel was inducted in the Green Bay Packers Hall of Fame on [[March 30]] [[1996]].<ref name=WGBA /> To honor his induction into the Packers Hall of Fame, the team built a new [[press box]] in August 2003, and they named it "The Lee Remmel Press Box".<ref name=WGBA /> Each April, the "Lee Remmel Sports Awards Banquet" honors high school to professional athletes;<ref name=WGBA /> the banquet has raised over $150,000 for Green Bay area colleges and high schools.<ref>{{cite web | title=Lee Remmel Banquet Goes on Without Remmel | work=[[WBAY]] | url = http://www.wbay.com/Global/story.asp?S=8151128&nav=menu24_4_7 | accessdate=May 7 | accessyear=2008}}</ref>

